# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: radar-spider-charts
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:radar-spider-charts/circular-layout] In graph drawing, a **circular layout** is a style of drawing that places the vertices of a graph on a circle, often evenly spaced so that they form the vertices of a regular polygon.
[src:radar-spider-charts/circular-layout] Circular layouts are a good fit for communications network topologies such as star or ring networks, and for the cyclic parts of metabolic networks.
[src:radar-spider-charts/circular-layout] For graphs with a known Hamiltonian cycle, a circular layout allows the cycle to be depicted as the circle, and in this way circular layouts form the basis of the LCF notation for Hamiltonian cubic graphs.
[src:radar-spider-charts/circular-layout] A circular layout may be used on its own for an entire graph drawing, but it also may be used as the layout for smaller clusters of vertices within a larger graph drawing, such as its biconnected components, clusters of genes in a gene interaction graph, or natural subgroups within a social network.
[src:radar-spider-charts/circular-layout] If multiple vertex circles are used in this way, other methods such as force-directed graph drawing may be used to arrange the clusters.
[src:radar-spider-charts/circular-layout] The edges of the drawing may be depicted as chords of the circle, as circular arcs (possibly perpendicular to the vertex circle, so that the edges model lines of the Poincaré disk model of hyperbolic geometry), or as other types of curve.
[src:radar-spider-charts/circular-layout] The visual distinction between the inside and the outside of the vertex circle in a circular layout may be used to separate two different styles of edge drawing.
[src:radar-spider-charts/circular-layout] For instance, a circular drawing algorithm of Gansner & Koren (2007) uses edge bundling within the circle, together with some edges that are not bundled, drawn outside the circle.
[src:radar-spider-charts/circular-layout] For circular layouts of regular graphs, with edges drawn both inside and outside as circular arcs, the angle of incidence of one of these arcs with the vertex circle is the same at both ends of the arc, a property that simplifies the optimization of the angular resolution of the drawing.
[src:radar-spider-charts/circular-layout] Several authors have studied the problem of finding a permutation of the vertices of a circular layout that minimizes the number of edge crossings when all edges are drawn inside the vertex circle.
[src:radar-spider-charts/circular-layout] This number of crossings is zero only for outerplanar graphs.
[src:radar-spider-charts/circular-layout] For other graphs, it may be optimized or reduced separately for each biconnected component of the graph before combining the solutions, as these components may be drawn so that they do not interact.
[src:radar-spider-charts/circular-layout] In general, minimizing the number of crossings is NP-complete.
[src:radar-spider-charts/circular-layout] (1995) described an approximation algorithm based on balanced cuts or edge separators, subsets of few edges whose removal disconnects the given graph into two subgraphs with approximately equal numbers of vertices.
[src:radar-spider-charts/circular-layout] After finding an approximate cut, their algorithm arranges the two subgraphs on each side of the cut recursively, without considering the additional crossings formed by the edges that cross the cut.
[src:radar-spider-charts/circular-layout] Their work cites a paper by Fan Chung and Shing-Tung Yau from 1994 that claimed $\rho =O(1)$ , but this was later found to have an erroneous proof.
[src:radar-spider-charts/circular-layout] Instead, the best approximation known for the balanced cut problem has $\rho =O({\sqrt {\log n}})$ , giving this circular layout algorithm an approximation ratio of $O(\log ^{3}n)$ on graphs that have a large number of crossings relative to their vertex degrees.
[src:radar-spider-charts/circular-layout] Heuristic methods for reducing the crossing complexity have also been devised, based e.g. on a careful vertex insertion order and on local optimization.
[src:radar-spider-charts/circular-layout] A circular layout may also be used to maximize the number of crossings.
[src:radar-spider-charts/circular-layout] In particular, choosing a random permutation for the vertices causes each possible crossing to occur with probability 1/3, so the expected number of crossings is within a factor of three of the maximum number of crossings among all possible layouts.
[src:radar-spider-charts/circular-layout] Derandomizing this method gives a deterministic approximation algorithm with approximation ratio three.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] In Euclidean geometry, a **kite** is a quadrilateral with reflection symmetry across a diagonal.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Because of this symmetry, a kite has two equal angles and two pairs of adjacent equal-length sides.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Kites are also known as **deltoids**, but the word *deltoid* may also refer to a deltoid curve, an unrelated geometric object sometimes studied in connection with quadrilaterals.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] A kite may also be called a **dart**, particularly if it is not convex.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Every kite is an orthodiagonal quadrilateral (its diagonals are at right angles) and, when convex, a tangential quadrilateral (its sides are tangent to an inscribed circle).
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] The convex kites are exactly the quadrilaterals that are both orthodiagonal and tangential.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] They include as special cases the right kites, with two opposite right angles; the rhombi, with two diagonal axes of symmetry; and the squares, which are also special cases of both right kites and rhombi.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] The quadrilateral with the greatest ratio of perimeter to diameter is a kite, with 60°, 75°, and 150° angles.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Kites of two shapes (one convex and one non-convex) form the prototiles of one of the forms of the Penrose tiling.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Kites also form the faces of several face-symmetric polyhedra and tessellations, and have been studied in connection with outer billiards, a problem in the advanced mathematics of dynamical systems.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] A kite is a quadrilateral with reflection symmetry across one of its diagonals.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Equivalently, it is a quadrilateral whose four sides can be grouped into two pairs of adjacent equal-length sides.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] A kite can be constructed from the centers and crossing points of any two intersecting circles.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Kites as described here may be either convex or concave, although some sources restrict *kite* to mean only convex kites.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Kite quadrilaterals are named for the wind-blown, flying kites, which often have this shape and which are in turn named for a hovering bird and the sound it makes.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] According to Olaus Henrici, the name "kite" was given to these shapes by James Joseph Sylvester.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Quadrilaterals can be classified *hierarchically*, meaning that some classes of quadrilaterals include other classes, or *partitionally*, meaning that each quadrilateral is in only one class.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Classified hierarchically, kites include the rhombi (quadrilaterals with four equal sides), squares, and Apollonius quadrilaterals (in which the products of opposite sides are equal).
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] All equilateral kites are rhombi, and all equiangular kites are squares.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] When classified partitionally, rhombi and squares would not be kites, because they belong to a different class of quadrilaterals; similarly, the right kites discussed below would not be kites.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] The remainder of this article follows a hierarchical classification; rhombi, squares, and right kites are all considered kites.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] By avoiding the need to consider special cases, this classification can simplify some facts about kites.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Like kites, a parallelogram also has two pairs of equal-length sides, but they are opposite to each other rather than adjacent.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Any non-self-crossing quadrilateral that has an axis of symmetry must be either a kite, with a diagonal axis of symmetry; or an isosceles trapezoid, with an axis of symmetry through the midpoints of two sides.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] These include as special cases the rhombus and the rectangle respectively, and the square, which is a special case of both.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] The self-crossing quadrilaterals include another class of symmetric quadrilaterals, the antiparallelograms.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] The right kites have two opposite right angles.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] The right kites are exactly the kites that are cyclic quadrilaterals, meaning that there is a circle that passes through all their vertices.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] The cyclic quadrilaterals may equivalently defined as the quadrilaterals in which two opposite angles are supplementary (they add to 180°); if one pair is supplementary the other is as well.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Therefore, the right kites are the kites with two opposite supplementary angles, for either of the two opposite pairs of angles.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Because right kites circumscribe one circle and are inscribed in another circle, they are bicentric quadrilaterals (actually tricentric, as they also have a third circle externally tangent to the extensions of their sides).
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] If the sizes of an inscribed and a circumscribed circle are fixed, the right kite has the largest area of any quadrilateral trapped between them.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Among all quadrilaterals, the shape that has the greatest ratio of its perimeter to its diameter (maximum distance between any two points) is an equidiagonal kite with angles 60°, 75°, 150°, 75°.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Its four vertices lie at the three corners and one of the side midpoints of the Reuleaux triangle.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] An equidiagonal kite is a special case of a midsquare quadrilateral.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] When an equidiagonal kite has side lengths less than or equal to its diagonals, like this one or the square, it is one of the quadrilaterals with the greatest ratio of area to diameter.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] A kite with three 108° angles and one 36° angle forms the convex hull of the lute of Pythagoras, a fractal made of nested pentagrams.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] The four sides of this kite lie on four of the sides of a regular pentagon, with a golden triangle glued onto the fifth side.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] There are only eight polygons that can tile the plane such that reflecting any tile across any one of its edges produces another tile; this arrangement is called an edge tessellation.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] One of them is a tiling by a right kite, with 60°, 90°, and 120° angles.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] It produces the deltoidal trihexagonal tiling (see § Tilings and polyhedra).
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] A prototile made by eight of these kites tiles the plane only aperiodically, key to a claimed solution of the einstein problem.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] In non-Euclidean geometry, a kite can have three right angles and one non-right angle, forming a special case of a Lambert quadrilateral.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] The fourth angle is acute in hyperbolic geometry and obtuse in spherical geometry.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Every kite is an orthodiagonal quadrilateral, meaning that its two diagonals are at right angles to each other.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Moreover, one of the two diagonals (the symmetry axis) is the perpendicular bisector of the other, and is also the angle bisector of the two angles it meets.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Because of its symmetry, the other two angles of the kite must be equal.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] The diagonal symmetry axis of a convex kite divides it into two congruent triangles; the other diagonal divides it into two isosceles triangles.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Every *convex* kite is also a tangential quadrilateral, a quadrilateral that has an inscribed circle.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] That is, there exists a circle that is tangent to all four sides.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Additionally, if a convex kite is not a rhombus, there is a circle outside the kite that is tangent to the extensions of the four sides; therefore, every convex kite that is not a rhombus is an ex-tangential quadrilateral.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] The convex kites that are not rhombi are exactly the quadrilaterals that are both tangential and ex-tangential.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Kites and isosceles trapezoids are dual to each other, meaning that there is a correspondence between them that reverses the dimension of their parts, taking vertices to sides and sides to vertices.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] From any kite, the inscribed circle is tangent to its four sides at the four vertices of an isosceles trapezoid.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] For any isosceles trapezoid, tangent lines to the circumscribing circle at its four vertices form the four sides of a kite.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] This correspondence can also be seen as an example of polar reciprocation, a general method for corresponding points with lines and vice versa given a fixed circle.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Although they do not touch the circle, the four vertices of the kite are reciprocal in this sense to the four sides of the isosceles trapezoid.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] The features of kites and isosceles trapezoids that correspond to each other under this duality are compared in the table below.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] The equidissection problem concerns the subdivision of polygons into triangles that all have equal areas.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] In this context, the *spectrum* of a polygon is the set of numbers n such that the polygon has an equidissection into n equal-area triangles.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Because of its symmetry, the spectrum of a kite contains all even integers.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Certain special kites also contain some odd numbers in their spectra.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Every triangle can be subdivided into three right kites meeting at the center of its inscribed circle.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] More generally, a method based on circle packing can be used to subdivide any polygon with n sides into $O(n)$ kites, meeting edge-to-edge.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] All kites tile the plane by repeated point reflection around the midpoints of their edges, as do more generally all quadrilaterals.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Kites and darts with angles 72°, 72°, 72°, 144° and 36°, 72°, 36°, 216°, respectively, form the prototiles of one version of the Penrose tiling, an aperiodic tiling of the plane discovered by mathematical physicist Roger Penrose.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] When a kite has angles that, at its apex and one side, sum to $\pi (1-{\tfrac {1}{n}})$ for some positive integer ⁠ n ⁠, then scaled copies of that kite can be used to tile the plane in a fractal rosette in which successively larger rings of n kites surround a central point.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] These rosettes can be used to study the phenomenon of inelastic collapse, in which a system of moving particles meeting in inelastic collisions all coalesce at a common point.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] A kite with angles 60°, 90°, 120°, 90° can also tile the plane by repeated reflection across its edges; the resulting tessellation, the deltoidal trihexagonal tiling, superposes a tessellation of the plane by regular hexagons and isosceles triangles.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] The deltoidal icositetrahedron, deltoidal hexecontahedron, and trapezohedron are polyhedra with congruent kite-shaped faces, which can alternatively be thought of as tilings of the sphere by congruent spherical kites.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] There are infinitely many face-symmetric tilings of the hyperbolic plane by kites.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] These polyhedra (equivalently, spherical tilings), the square and deltoidal trihexagonal tilings of the Euclidean plane, and some tilings of the hyperbolic plane are shown in the table below, labeled by face configuration (the numbers of neighbors of each of the four vertices of each tile).
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Some polyhedra and tilings appear twice, under two different face configurations.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] The trapezohedra are another family of polyhedra that have congruent kite-shaped faces.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] In these polyhedra, the edges of one of the two side lengths of the kite meet at two "pole" vertices, while the edges of the other length form an equatorial zigzag path around the polyhedron.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] They are the dual polyhedra of the uniform antiprisms.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] A commonly seen example is the pentagonal trapezohedron, used for ten-sided dice.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Mathematician Richard Schwartz has studied outer billiards on kites.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] Outer billiards is a dynamical system in which, from a point outside a given compact convex set in the plane, one draws a tangent line to the convex set, travels from the starting point along this line to another point equally far from the point of tangency, and then repeats the same process.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] He later wrote a monograph analyzing outer billiards for kite shapes more generally.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] The behavior of outer billiards on any kite depends strongly on the parameter $\alpha$ and in particular whether it is rational.
[src:radar-spider-charts/kite-geometry] For the case of the Penrose kite, ⁠ $\textstyle \alpha =1/\varphi ^{3}$ ⁠, an irrational number, where ⁠ $\varphi ={\tfrac {1}{2}}{\bigl (}1+{\sqrt {5}}~\!{\bigr )}$ ⁠ is the golden ratio.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] In mathematics, the **polar coordinate system** specifies a given point in a plane by using a distance and an angle as its two coordinates.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The distance from the pole is called the *radial coordinate*, *radial distance* or simply *radius*, and the angle is called the *angular coordinate*, *polar angle*, or *azimuth*.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The pole is analogous to the origin in a Cartesian coordinate system.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Polar coordinates are most appropriate in any context where the phenomenon being considered is inherently tied to direction and length from a center point in a plane, such as spirals.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Planar physical systems with bodies moving around a central point, or phenomena originating from a central point, are often simpler and more intuitive to model using polar coordinates.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The polar coordinate system is extended to three dimensions in two ways: the cylindrical coordinate system adds a second distance coordinate, and the spherical coordinate system adds a second angular coordinate.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Grégoire de Saint-Vincent and Bonaventura Cavalieri independently introduced the system's concepts in the mid-17th century, though the actual term *polar coordinates* has been attributed to Gregorio Fontana in the 18th century.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The initial motivation for introducing the polar system was the study of circular and orbital motion.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The concepts of angle and radius were already used by ancient peoples of the first millennium BC.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The Greek astronomer Hipparchus (190–120 BC) created a table of chord functions giving the length of the chord for each angle, and there are references to his using polar coordinates in establishing stellar positions.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] In *On Spirals*, Greek mathematician Archimedes describes his spiral, a function whose radius depends on the angle.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The Greek work, however, did not extend to a full coordinate system.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] From the 8th century AD onward, astronomers developed methods for approximating and calculating the direction to Mecca (qibla)—and its distance—from any location on the Earth.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] From the 9th century onward they were using spherical trigonometry and map projection methods to determine these quantities accurately.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] There are various accounts of the introduction of polar coordinates as part of a formal coordinate system.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The full history of the subject is described in Harvard professor Julian Lowell Coolidge's *Origin of Polar Coordinates.* Mathematicians from Jesuit, Grégoire de Saint-Vincent, and Italian Bonaventura Cavalieri independently introduced the concepts in the mid-seventeenth century.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Saint-Vincent wrote about them privately in 1625 and published his work in 1647, while Cavalieri published his in 1635, with a corrected version appearing in 1653.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Cavalieri first used polar coordinates to solve a problem relating to the area within an Archimedean spiral.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] French mathematician Blaise Pascal subsequently used polar coordinates to calculate the length of parabolic arcs.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] In *Method of Fluxions* (written 1671, published 1736), English mathematician Sir Isaac Newton examined the transformations between polar coordinates, which he referred to as the "Seventh Manner; For Spirals", and nine other coordinate systems.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] He is credited with originating the polar coordinate system in its analytic form and for originating bipolar coordinates in a strict sense.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] In the journal *Acta Eruditorum* (1691), Swiss mathematician Jacob Bernoulli used a system with a point on a line, called the *pole* and *polar axis* respectively.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Coordinates were specified by the distance from the pole and the angle from the *polar axis*.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Bernoulli's work extended to the calculation of the radius of curvature of curves expressed in these coordinates.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The term *polar coordinates* was attributed to Gregorio Fontana and used by 18th-century Italian writers.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The term appeared in English in George Peacock's 1816 translation of Lacroix's *Differential and Integral Calculus*.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Alexis Clairaut was the first to think of polar coordinates in three dimensions, and Leonhard Euler was the first to actually develop them.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The radial coordinate is often denoted by r or $\rho$ (rho).
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The angular coordinate is denoted by $\varphi$ (phi), specified by ISO standard 31-11 (now 80000-2:2019), or $\theta$ (theta) in mathematical literature oftentimes.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Angles in polar notation are generally expressed in either degrees or radians (2π rad being equal to 360°).
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Degrees are traditionally used in navigation, surveying, and many applied disciplines, while radians are more common in mathematics and mathematical physics.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The angle $\varphi$ is defined to start at 0° from a *reference direction*, and to increase for rotations in either clockwise (↻) or counterclockwise (↺) orientation.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The polar angles decrease towards negative values for rotations in the respective opposite orientations.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Adding any number of full turns (360°) to the angular coordinate does not change the corresponding direction.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Similarly, any polar coordinate is identical to the coordinate with the negative radial component and the opposite direction (adding 180° to the polar angle).
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Therefore, the same point $(r,\varphi )$ can be expressed with an infinite number of different polar coordinates $(r,\varphi +n\times 360^{\circ })$ and $(-r,\varphi +180^{\circ }+n\times 360^{\circ })=(-r,\varphi +(2n+1)\times 180^{\circ })$ , where n is an arbitrary integer.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Moreover, the pole itself can be expressed as $(0,\varphi )$ for any angle $\varphi$ .
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Where a unique representation is needed for any point besides the pole, it is usual to limit r to positive numbers ( $r>0$ ) and $\varphi$ to either the interval $[0,360^{\circ })$ or the interval $(-180^{\circ },180^{\circ }]$ , which in radians are $[0,2\pi )$ or $(-\pi ,\pi ]$ .
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Another convention, in reference to the usual codomain of the arctan function, is to allow for arbitrary nonzero real values of the radial component and restrict the polar angle to $(-90^{\circ },90^{\circ }]$ .
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] In all cases, a unique azimuth for the pole $r=0$ must be chosen, e.g., $\varphi =0$ .
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] A complex number consists of real numbers x and y , as well as an imaginary number $i^{2}=-1$ , which can be written as $z=x+iy$ .
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Every complex number represents a point in the complex plane, thereby expressible by specifying either the point's Cartesian coordinates (called rectangular or Cartesian form) or the point's polar coordinates (called polar form).
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] In polar form, the distance r and angle coordinate $\varphi$ are often referred to as the number's magnitude of modulus and argument, respectively.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] To convert between the rectangular and polar forms of a complex number, the conversion formulae given above can be used.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] For the operations of multiplication, division, exponentiation, and root extraction of complex numbers, it is generally much simpler to work with complex numbers expressed in polar form rather than rectangular form.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The equation defining a plane curve expressed in polar coordinates is known as a *polar equation*.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] In many cases, such an equation can simply be specified by defining *r* as a function of *φ*.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The resulting curve then consists of points of the form (*r*(*φ*), *φ*) and can be regarded as the graph of the polar function *r*.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Note that, in contrast to Cartesian coordinates, the independent variable *φ* is the *second* entry in the ordered pair.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Because of the circular nature of the polar coordinate system, many curves can be described by a rather simple polar equation, whereas their Cartesian form is much more intricate.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Among the best known of these curves are the polar rose, Archimedean spiral, lemniscate, limaçon, and cardioid.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] For the circle, line, and polar rose below, it is understood that there are no restrictions on the domain and range of the curve.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] This can be simplified in various ways, to conform to more specific cases, such as the equation $r(\varphi )=a$ for a circle with a center at the pole and radius *a*.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] In the general case, the equation can be solved for *r*, giving $r=r_{0}\cos(\varphi -\gamma )+{\sqrt {a^{2}-r_{0}^{2}\sin ^{2}(\varphi -\gamma )}}$ The solution with a minus sign in front of the square root gives the same curve.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] If $\epsilon >1$ , this equation defines a hyperbola; if $\epsilon =1$ , it defines a parabola; and if $\epsilon <1$ , it defines an ellipse.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The special case $\epsilon =0$ of the latter results in a circle of the radius $\ell$ .
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Both are special cases of *r*(*φ*) = *a* cos(*kφ + γ*), with *γ* determining the phase and equivalently the rotation.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] If *k* is an integer, these equations will produce a *k*-petaled rose if *k* is odd, or a 2*k*-petaled rose if *k* is even.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] If *k* is rational, but not an integer, a rose-like shape may form, but with overlapping petals.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Note that these equations never define a rose with 2, 6, 10, 14, etc. petals.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The variable *a* directly represents the length or amplitude of the petals of the rose, while *k* relates to their spatial frequency.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The Archimedean spiral is a spiral discovered by Archimedes, which can also be expressed as a simple polar equation.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] It is represented by the equation $r(\varphi )=a+b\varphi .$ Changing the parameter *a* will turn the spiral, while *b* controls the distance between the arms, which for a given spiral is always constant.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The Archimedean spiral has two arms, one for *φ* > 0 and one for *φ* < 0.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The two arms are smoothly connected at the pole.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] If *a* = 0, taking the mirror image of one arm across the 90°/270° line will yield the other arm.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] This curve is notable as one of the first curves, after the conic sections, to be described in a mathematical treatise, and as a prime example of a curve best defined by a polar equation.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] A quadratrix in the first quadrant $(x,y)$ is a curve with $y=\rho \sin \theta$ equal to the fraction of the quarter circle with radius r determined by the radius through the curve point.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] All the points $[g(\theta _{i}),\theta _{i}]$ where $\theta _{i}$ are solutions to the equation $f(\theta +2k\pi )=g(\theta )$ where k is an integer.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] All the points $[g(\theta _{i}),\theta _{i}]$ where $\theta _{i}$ are solutions to the equation $f(\theta +(2k+1)\pi )=-g(\theta )$ where k is an integer.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Calculus can be applied to equations expressed in polar coordinates.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The angular coordinate *φ* is expressed in radians throughout this section, which is the conventional choice when doing calculus.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Using *x* = *r* cos *φ* and *y* = *r* sin *φ*, one can derive a relationship between derivatives in Cartesian and polar coordinates.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Using the inverse coordinates transformation, an analogous reciprocal relationship can be derived between the derivatives.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] For other useful formulas including divergence, gradient, and Laplacian in polar coordinates, see curvilinear coordinates.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The arc length (length of a line segment) defined by a polar function is found by the integration over the curve *r*(*φ*).
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Let *L* denote this length along the curve starting from points *A* through to point *B*, where these points correspond to *φ* = *a* and *φ* = *b* such that 0 < *b* − *a* < 2*π*.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Let *R* denote the region enclosed by a curve *r*(*φ*) and the rays *φ* = *a* and *φ* = *b*, where 0 < *b* − *a* ≤ 2π.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] First, the interval [*a*, *b*] is divided into *n* subintervals, where *n* is some positive integer.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Thus Δ*φ*, the angle measure of each subinterval, is equal to *b* − *a* (the total angle measure of the interval), divided by *n*, the number of subintervals.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] For each subinterval *i* = 1, 2, ..., *n*, let *φ**i* be the midpoint of the subinterval, and construct a sector with the center at the pole, radius *r*(*φ**i*), central angle Δ*φ* and arc length *r*(*φ**i*)Δ*φ*.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] As the number of subintervals *n* is increased, the approximation of the area improves.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Taking *n* → ∞, the sum becomes the Riemann sum for the above integral.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Using Cartesian coordinates, an infinitesimal area element can be calculated as *dA* = *dx* *dy*.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Here, *R* is the same region as above, namely, the region enclosed by a curve *r*(*φ*) and the rays *φ* = *a* and *φ* = *b*.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The formula for the area of *R* is retrieved by taking *f* identically equal to 1.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Vector calculus can also be applied to polar coordinates.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] For a planar motion, let $\mathbf {r}$ be the position vector (*r* cos(*φ*), *r* sin(*φ*)), with *r* and *φ* depending on time *t*.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] We define an orthonormal basis with three unit vectors: *radial, transverse, and normal directions*.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The term $r{\dot {\varphi }}^{2}$ is sometimes referred to as the *centripetal acceleration*, and the term $2{\dot {r}}{\dot {\varphi }}$ as the *Coriolis acceleration*.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] These terms, which appear when acceleration is expressed in polar coordinates, are a mathematical consequence of differentiation; they appear whenever polar coordinates are used.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] In planar particle dynamics, these accelerations appear when setting up Newton's second law of motion in a rotating frame of reference.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Here, these extra terms are often called fictitious forces; fictitious because they are simply a result of a change in coordinate frame.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] That does not mean they do not exist; rather, they exist only in the rotating frame.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] , always points radially from the origin.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] , not parallel to the radial motion but offset by the angular and Coriolis accelerations, nor tangent to the path but offset by the centripetal and radial accelerations.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Kinematic vectors in plane polar coordinates.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Notice the setup is not restricted to two-dimensional space, but a plane in any higher dimension.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] For a particle in planar motion, one approach to attaching physical significance to these terms is based on the concept of an instantaneous **co-rotating frame of reference**.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] To define a co-rotating frame of reference, first an origin is selected from which the distance *r*(*t*) to the particle is defined.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] An axis of rotation is set up that is perpendicular to the plane of motion of the particle, and passing through this origin.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Then, at the selected moment *t*, the angular rate of the co-rotating frame Ω is made to match the rate of rotation of the particle about this axis, *dφ*/*dt*.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Next, the terms in the acceleration in the inertial frame are related to those in the co-rotating frame.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Let the location of the particle in the inertial frame be (*r*(*t*), *φ*(*t*)), and in the co-rotating frame be denoted primed (*r*′(t), *φ*′(t)).
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Because the co-rotating frame rotates at the same rate as the particle, *dφ*′/*dt* = 0.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The fictitious centrifugal force in the co-rotating frame is *mr*Ω2, radially outward.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The velocity of the particle in the co-rotating frame also is radially outward, because *dφ*′/*dt* = 0.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The *fictitious Coriolis force* therefore has a value −2*m*(*dr*/*dt*)Ω, pointed in the direction of increasing *φ* only.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Thus, using these forces in Newton's second law we find: $\mathbf {F} +\mathbf {F} _{\text{cf}}+\mathbf {F} _{\text{Cor}}=m{\ddot {\mathbf {r} }}\,,$ where over dots represent derivatives with respect to time, and **F** is the net real force (as opposed to the fictitious forces).
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] For general motion of a particle (as opposed to simple circular motion), the centrifugal and Coriolis forces in a particle's frame of reference commonly are referred to the instantaneous osculating circle of its motion, not to a fixed center of polar coordinates.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] In the modern terminology of differential geometry, polar coordinates provide coordinate charts for the differentiable manifold **R**2 \ {(0,0)}, the plane minus the origin.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Therefore, as expected, the punctured plane is a flat manifold.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The polar coordinate system is extended into three dimensions with two different coordinate systems, the cylindrical and spherical coordinate systems, both of which include two-dimensional or planar polar coordinates as a subset.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] In essence, the cylindrical coordinate system extends polar coordinates by adding an additional distance coordinate, while the spherical system instead adds an additional angular coordinate.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The cylindrical coordinate system is a coordinate system that essentially extends the two-dimensional polar coordinate system by adding a third coordinate measuring the height of a point above the plane, similar to the way in which the Cartesian coordinate system is extended into three dimensions.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The third coordinate is denoted z , making the three cylindrical coordinates $(r,\theta ,z)$ .
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Polar coordinates can also be extended into three dimensions using the coordinates (ρ, φ, θ), where ρ is the distance from the pole, φ is the angle from the z-axis (called the colatitude or zenith and measured from 0 to 180°), and θ is the angle from the x-axis (as in the polar coordinates).
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] This coordinate system, called the spherical coordinate system, is similar to the latitude and longitude system used for Earth, with the latitude δ being the complement of φ, determined by δ = 90° − φ, and the longitude *l* being measured by *l* = θ − 180°.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Polar coordinates are two-dimensional and thus they can be used only where point positions lie on a single two-dimensional plane.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] They are most appropriate in any context where the phenomenon being considered is inherently tied to direction and length from a center point.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] For instance, the examples above show how elementary polar equations suffice to define curves—such as the Archimedean spiral—whose equation in the Cartesian coordinate system would be much more intricate.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Moreover, many physical systems—such as those concerned with bodies moving around a central point or with phenomena originating from a central point—are simpler and more intuitive to model using polar coordinates.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The initial motivation for the introduction of the polar system was the study of circular and orbital motion.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Polar coordinates are used often in navigation as the destination or direction of travel can be given as an angle and distance from the object being considered.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] For instance, aircraft use a slightly modified version of the polar coordinates for navigation.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] In this system, the one generally used for any sort of navigation, the 0° ray is generally called heading 360, and the angles continue in a clockwise direction, rather than counterclockwise, as in the mathematical system.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Heading 360 corresponds to magnetic north, while headings 90, 180, and 270 correspond to magnetic east, south, and west, respectively.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Thus, an aircraft traveling 5 nautical miles due east will be traveling 5 units at heading 90 (read zero-niner-zero by air traffic control).
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Systems displaying radial symmetry provide natural settings for the polar coordinate system, with the central point acting as the pole.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] A prime example of this usage is the groundwater flow equation when applied to radially symmetric wells.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Systems with a radial force are also good candidates for the use of the polar coordinate system.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] These systems include gravitational fields, which obey the inverse-square law, as well as systems with point sources, such as radio antennas.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] Radially asymmetric systems may also be modeled with polar coordinates.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] For example, a microphone's pickup pattern illustrates its proportional response to an incoming sound from a given direction, and these patterns can be represented as polar curves.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The curve for a standard cardioid microphone, the most common unidirectional microphone, can be represented as *r* = 0.5 + 0.5sin(*ϕ*) at its target design frequency.
[src:radar-spider-charts/polar-coordinate-system] The pattern shifts toward omnidirectionality at lower frequencies.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] A **radar chart** is a graphical method of displaying multivariate data in the form of a two-dimensional chart of three or more quantitative variables represented on axes starting from the same point.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Radar charts are also known as **web charts**, **spider charts**, **spider graphs**, **spider web charts**, **star charts**, **star plots**, **cobweb charts**, **irregular polygons**, **polar charts**, and **Kiviat diagrams**.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] It is equivalent to a parallel coordinates plot, with the axes arranged radially.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] The radar chart is a chart and/or plot that consists of a sequence of equi-angular spokes, called radii, with each spoke representing one of the variables.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] The data length of a spoke is proportional to the magnitude of the variable for the data point relative to the maximum magnitude of the variable across all data points.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] A line is drawn connecting the data values for each spoke.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] This gives the plot a star-like appearance and the origin of one of the popular names for this plot.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Radar charts are a useful way to display multivariate observations with an arbitrary number of variables.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Each star represents a single observation.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Typically, radar charts are generated in a multi-plot format with many stars on each page and each star representing one observation.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] The star plot was first used by Georg von Mayr in 1877.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Radar charts differ from glyph plots in that all variables are used to construct the plotted star figure.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] There is no separation into foreground and background variables.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Instead, the star-shaped figures are usually arranged in a rectangular array on the page.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] It is somewhat easier to see patterns in the data if the observations are arranged in some non-arbitrary order (if the variables are assigned to the rays of the star in some meaningful order).
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Radar charts can be used in sports to chart players' strengths and weaknesses by calculating various statistics related to the player that can tracked along the central axis of the chart.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Examples include a basketball players shots made, rebounds, assists, etc., or the batting or pitching stats of a baseball player.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] This creates a centralized visualization of the strengths and weaknesses of a player, and if overlapped with the statistics of other players or league averages, can display where a player excels and where they could improve.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] These insights into player strengths and weakness could prove crucial to player development as it allows coaches and trainers to adjust a player's training regiment to help improve on their weaknesses.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] The results of the radar chart can also be useful in situational play.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] If a batter is shown to hit poorly against left-handed pitching, then his team knows to limit his plate appearances against left-handed pitchers, while the opposing team may try to force a situation where the batter is forced to hit against the pitcher.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Another application of radar charts is the control of quality improvement to display the performance metrics various objects including computer programs, computers, phones, vehicles, and more.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Computer programmer often use analytics to test the performance of their programs versus others.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] An example of this where radar charts may be useful is the performance analysis of various sorting algorithms.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Another performance application is measuring the performance of similar cars against each other.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] A consumer could look at variables such as the cars' top speed, miles per gallon, horsepower, and torque.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Then after using a radar chart to visualize the data, they could decide on what car is best for them based on the results.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Radar charts can be used in life sciences to display the strengths and weakness of drugs and other medications.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Using the example of two anti-depressants, a researcher can rank variables such as efficacy, side effects, cost, etc. on a scale of one to ten.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] They could then graph the results using a radar chart to see the spread of variables and find how the differ, such as one anti-depressant being cheaper and quicker acting, but not having great relief over time.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Meanwhile, the other anti-depressant provides stronger relief and holds up better over time but is more expensive.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Another life science application is in patient analysis.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Radar charts can be used to graph the variables of life affecting a person's wellness, and then be analyzed to help them.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] A more specific example is in the case of athletes, whose various wellness habits such as sleep, diet, and stress are monitored to make sure they stay in peak physical condition.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] If any areas would be shown dipping, doctors and trainers could step in to assist the athlete and improve their wellness.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Radar charts are primarily suited for strikingly showing *outliers* and *commonality*, or when one chart is greater in every variable than another, and primarily used for ordinal measurements where each variable corresponds to "better" in some respect and all variables are on the same scale.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Conversely, radar charts have been criticized as poorly suited for making trade-off decisions when one chart is greater than another on some variables, but less on others.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Further, it is hard to visually compare lengths of different spokes, because radial distances are hard to judge, though concentric circles help as grid lines.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Instead, one may use a simple line graph, particularly for a time series.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Radar charts can distort data to some extent, especially when areas are filled in, because the area contained becomes proportional to the square of the linear measures.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] For example, in a chart with 5 variables that range from 1 to 100, the area contained by the polygon bounded by 5 points when all measures are 90 is more than 10% larger than the same for a chart with all values of 82.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Radar charts can also become hard to visually compare between different samples on the chart when their values are close as their lines or areas bleed into each other, as shown in Figure 5.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] For example, the alternating data 9, 1, 9, 1, 9, 1 yields a spiking radar chart (which goes in and out), while reordering the data as 9, 9, 9, 1, 1, 1 instead yields two distinct wedges (sectors).
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] In some cases there is a natural structure, and radar charts can be well-suited.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] For example, for diagrams of data that vary over a 24-hour cycle, each hour's data is naturally related to its neighbor and the overall data has a cyclic structure, so it can naturally be displayed as a radar chart.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Radar charts are helpful for small-to-moderate-sized multivariate data sets.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Their primary weakness is that their effectiveness is limited to data sets with less than a few hundred points.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] After that, they tend to be overwhelming.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Further, when using radar charts with multiple dimensions or samples, the radar chart may become cluttered and harder to interpret as the number of samples grows.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] For example, take the batting stats table comparing MLB 2021 MVP Shohei Ohtani, vs the stats of the leagues average designated hitters and some Hall of Fame players.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] These stats represent the percentage of hits, home runs, strike outs, etc. per at bat of a player.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] For more information on what each stat used in the table represents, you can refer to this reference by the MLB.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] We will use this table below to create Radar charts comparing the 2021 MVP batting stats to the league averages for Designated Hitters and regular batters, in an attempt to visualize performance metrics and visually come to a conclusion that Shohei out performed the average player.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Next we will include additional samples into the Radar chart, using Hall of Fame players Jackie Robinson, Jim Thome, and Frank Thomas to compare Shohei to a few of the greatest batters of all time.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] This Radar chart not only can give us intuition of how Shohei compares to the top historical players, but will also serve a purpose in showing the limitations of having too many samples in a Radar chart.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] We can see in Figure 10 how a radar chart can be easily interpreted when the number of spokes and samples is relatively small.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] When we compare more samples in Figure 11, even without an area fill on the radar chart, it becomes apparent how difficult it can become to interpret or make trade-off decisions.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] The chart on the right contains the star plots of 15 cars.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] We can look at these plots individually or we can use them to identify clusters of cars with similar features.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] For example, we can look at the star plot of the Cadillac Seville (the last one on the image) and see that it is one of the most expensive cars, gets below average (but not among the worst) gas mileage, has an average repair record, and has average-to-above-average roominess and size.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] We can then compare the Cadillac models (the last three plots) with the AMC models (the first three plots).
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] This comparison shows distinct patterns.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] The AMC models tend to be inexpensive, have below average gas mileage, and are small in both height and weight and in roominess.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] The Cadillac models are expensive, have poor gas mileage, and are large in both size and roominess.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] One may use line graphs for time series and other data, in the form of parallel coordinates.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] For graphical qualitative comparison of 2-dimensional tabular data in several variables, a common alternative are Harvey balls, which are used extensively by *Consumer Reports*.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Comparison in Harvey balls (and radar charts) may be significantly aided by ordering the variables algorithmically to add order.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] An excellent way for visualising structures within multivariate data is offered by principal component analysis (PCA).
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Another alternative is to use small, inline bar charts, which may be compared to sparklines.
[src:radar-spider-charts/radar-chart] Although radar and polar charts are often described as the same chart types, some sources make a difference between them and even consider the radar chart to be a polar chart's variation that does not display data in terms of polar coordinate.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] A **visual variable**, in cartographic design, graphic design, and data visualization, is an aspect of a graphical object that can visually differentiate it from other objects, and can be controlled during the design process.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Graphic techniques have been used in maps and statistical charts to represent non-visual information since the 17th Century, and information visualization blossomed in the 19th Century, highlighted by the work of William Playfair and Charles Joseph Minard.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] However, the direct study of this abstract use of graphical appearance began with the emergence of cartography as an academic research discipline in the mid-20th Century.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] In *The Look of Maps* (1952), often considered the genesis of American cartographic theory, Arthur H.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Robinson discussed the role of size, shape, and color in establishing contrast in maps.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] At the same time in France, Jacques Bertin published an early version of his list of visual variables: shape, value, and "sparkling" (grain).
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Robinson, in his 1960 *Elements of Cartography*, which quickly became the dominant textbook on the subject, discussed size, shape, color, and pattern as the qualities of map symbols that establish contrast and represent geographic information.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Bertin was a cartographer at the École pratique des hautes études (EPHE) in Paris, where he created maps and graphics for faculty from various disciplines using a wide variety of data.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Despite having a background in cartography, and deriving many of his ideas by evaluating maps, he intended for *Sémiologie Graphique* to be applied to all forms of graphic design and information visualization.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Soon the idea was gaining international acceptance; in 1974 Joel Morrison presented a very similar system in the context of cartographic generalization, citing neither Bertin nor Robinson but saying that it was a "traditional categorization," suggesting its widespread nature by that point.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Despite the title of Bertin's work, it actually contained little reference to the scientific knowledge in the field of Semiotics or any other, and was primarily a practical summation of patterns he found in practice.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] The "truth" of the visual variables concept was largely established by its widespread and long-lasting acceptance.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] The earliest lists commonly suggested six variables: location size, shape, value, hue, orientation, and grain (pattern spacing).
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] To this list, several additions have been suggested, with a few entering the canonical lists found in textbooks, while other suggestions have largely been dropped in cartography.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] With the rise of multimedia as a cartographic tool, analogous sets of non-visual communication variables have also been presented.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Starting with Robinson and Bertin, a core set of visual variables has become largely canonical, appearing in cartography and information visualization textbooks, and built into most design software in some form.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] The size of a symbol is how much space it occupies.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] This commonly refers to the area of point symbols, and the thickness of line symbols.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Size differences are relatively easy to recognize, making it a useful variable to convey information, such as a quantitative amount of something, or relative importance.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Studies have shown that humans are better at judging relative differences in linear distance (e.g. one road being twice as thick as another) than relative differences in area (e.g., one circle having twice the area of another).
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Such estimations are the most accurate from squares.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Area differences of circles are generally underestimated, but there is a large variation between people in ability to estimate two-dimensional size.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Correctly estimating relative volume has proven even more difficult.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Because geographical features have an actual size on the Earth, this cannot always be controlled, and sometimes works against the wishes of a cartographer; for example, it can be difficult to make a world map in which Russia does not stand out.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] In a cartogram the size of features is purposefully distorted to represent a variable other than area.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] A shape is a simple design that is used to symbolize an attribute on a map.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Shape is most commonly attached to point features in maps.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Some shapes are simple in nature and thus are more abstract, while other shapes are more pictorial and are easy for the reader to comprehend what is trying to be conveyed.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Some aspects of shape are inherent to the phenomenon and may not be easily manipulable, especially in line and region symbols, such as the shape of a road or a country.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] However, shape can still play a role in line and region symbols, such as a region filled with tree symbols or an arrowhead on a line.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Also, the shape of a feature may be purposefully distorted by Cartographic generalization, especially when creating schematic representations such as many transit maps, although this distortion is rarely used to convey information, only to reduce emphasis on shape and location.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] As an aspect of color, **value** refers to how light or dark an object appears.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Value effectively connotes "more" and "less," an ordinal measure; this makes it a very useful form of symbology in thematic maps, especially choropleth maps.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Value contributes strongly to Visual hierarchy; elements that contrast most with the value of the background tend to stand out most (e.g., black on a white sheet of paper, white on a black computer screen).
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] The **saturation** of a color is its purity or intensity, created by the variety of light composing it; a single wavelength of light is of the highest saturation, while white, black, or gray has no saturation (being an even mixture of all visible wavelengths).
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Of the three psychological aspects of color, this is the least effective at conveying specific information, but it is very effective at establishing figure-ground and visual hierarchy, with bright colors generally standing out more than muted tones or shades of gray.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Bertin mentions saturation in his discussion of "color" (hue), but did not include it as a distinct variable.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Orientation refers to the direction labels and symbols are facing on a map (occasionally called "direction" or "angle").
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Although it is not used as often as many of the other visual variables, it can be useful for communicating information about the real-world orientation of features.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Common examples include wind direction and the direction in which a spring flows.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Although terminology for this aspect still varies somewhat today, *texture* or *pattern* in this context generally refers to an aggregate symbol composed of recurring sub-symbols.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] This can include areas (such as a forest filled with small tree point symbols) and line symbols (such as a railroad with recurring cross-hatches).
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] The amount of white space between the sub-symbols in the pattern.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Bertin's French term *grain* was translated as "texture" in the 1983 English edition, and appeared frequently as such in subsequent lists, but others have suggested that *granularity* or just *grain* is a better translation.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] The orderliness of the location of the sub-symbols in the pattern, generally either regularly spaced in rows and columns (often indicating a human construction, such as an orchard), or randomly spaced (often indicating a natural distribution).
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] A number of additional variables have been suggested at times.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Some are recent technology-driven proposals, while others are earlier entries that have fallen out of favor.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] The absolute location of the symbol in the design, specified as (x,y) coordinates.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] This was a core part of Bertin's model, who distinguished these "imposition variables" from the other "retinal variables." This has largely been dropped from most subsequent lists by cartographers, since location in a map is predetermined by geography.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] However, it is crucial for representing information in charts and other data visualizations; for example, position is the main method of visualizing quantitative values in a scatterplot.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Even in cartography, position becomes a variable when labeling and laying out the non-map elements on the page.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] It is also relevant when representing fields; for example, the location of an isoline is an abstract visualization of a property, not the location of a real-world linear feature.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] In a regular arrangement, the direction in which the sub-symbols are arrayed.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Bertin considered this just the area version of the primary variable of orientation, but Morrison included it as a separate variable, likely because the orientation of the individual sub-symbols may be different than the angle in which they are arranged.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] In recent years, it has rarely been included, likely due to the overall decrease in the use of fill patterns in the era of digital cartography.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] These corollary terms refer to the degree to which a symbol blends with other symbols at the same location, giving the illusion of the symbol in front being translucent.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] A fairly recent addition, the control of opacity has become common in digital cartography.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] While it is rarely used to convey specific information, it is effective for reducing contrast or to retain underlying information.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Despite its widespread use, it is rarely mentioned in textbooks.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] This is the degree to which a symbol is drawn with crisp or fuzzy edges.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Briefly mentioned in the *Elements* textbook in 1978, the concept was more fully developed by Alan MacEachren in 1992 as a tool for representing locational uncertainty; he first called it *focus*, then chose *crispness*, which has been the most common term in subsequent lists.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] This is the technique of purposefully pixelating a symbol or feature as a way of generalizing and obscuring it, usually for communicating some form of uncertainty about the feature.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] This was also first introduced in that context by MacEachren, but is not commonly used, and has rarely been mentioned since.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] By extension, this can also refer to the general level of detail in a symbol, which is used more often than pixelation, especially in the context of cartographic generalization.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] On three-dimensional perspective maps, it is common to extrude shapes in the z direction, so that height represents a property.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] According to Bertin, each of the visual variables suggests its own mode of perception and interpretation, which MacEachren ties to the cognitive theory of Image schema (e.g., size: Large-small ~ more-less).
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] These modes make each variable better for representing certain kinds of information, and serving certain purposes, than others.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Specifically, Bertin introduces four properties of these variables, which tie them directly to their role in the visual hierarchy and to their ability to represent data in each of Steven's levels of measurement.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Each of these variables may be employed to convey information, to provide contrast between different features and layers, to establish figure-ground contrast and a clear visual hierarchy, or add to the aesthetic appeal of the map.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Map symbols commonly employ multiple visual variables simultaneously.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] This can be used to reinforce the depiction of a single property; for example, a capital city having a symbol that is larger and a different shape than other cities, or a color progression on a choropleth map from pale yellow to dark green, using both hue and value.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Alternatively, different visual variables may be used to represent different properties; for example, symbols for cities may be differentiated by size to indicate population, and by shape to indicate provincial and national capitals.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] Some visual variable can be combined harmoniously to make a map clearer and more informative, while other combinations tend to add more confusion than usefulness.
[src:radar-spider-charts/visual-variable] For example, early experiments with using Chernoff faces on maps have been criticized as difficult to interpret correctly.
